'''Alexander Mosby Clayton''' (January 15, 1801 – September 30, 1889) was an American politician who served as a Deputy from [[Mississippi]] to the [[Provisional Congress of the Confederate States]] from February to May 1861.

==Biography==
Clayton was born in [[Campbell County, Virginia]]. He migrated first to [[Arkansas]], where he served on the Territorial Supreme Court in 1832, then to [[Mississippi]] where he served as a state court judge from 1842 to 1852. In 1853 he served as United States consul in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]. He represented the state in the [[Provisional Confederate States Congress|Provisional C.S. Congress]] from February to May, 1861. He resigned and was appointed as a [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] District Court Judge for the balance of the year. After the war he again served as a state court judge from 1866 to 1869.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}

