'''Jean d'Espagnet''' (1564 – c. 1637) was a French [[The Renaissance|Renaissance]] [[polymath]]. He was a lawyer and politician, a mathematician and [[Alchemy|alchemist]], an [[antiquarian]], poet and friend of French literati.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Willard|first1=Thomas|editor1-last=Debus|editor1-first=Allen G.|editor2-last=Walton|editor2-first=Michael T.|title="The Many Worlds of Jean D’Espagnet" in Reading the Book of Nature: The Other Side of the Scientific Revolution, Sixteenth Century Essays and Studies, volume 41|date=1998|publisher=Thomas Jefferson Press at Truman State University|isbn=9780940474475|page=202|url=https://www.academia.edu/1561808/_The_Many_Worlds_of_Jean_dEspagnet_|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>
D'Espagnet was a counsellor in the [[Parlement]] of [[Bordeaux]] and its president from the years 1600 to 1611.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titi Lucretii Cari De rerum natura libri sex (Montaigne.1.4.4)|url=http://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-MONTAIGNE-00001-00004-00004/1|publisher=Cambridge Digital Library|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> In this position he was involved, with [[Pierre de Lancre]], in [[witch-hunting]] in [[Labourd]]. D'Espagnet contributed to de Lancre's 1607 work on witchcraft.
His son [[Étienne d'Espagnet]] utilised his father's library and designed optics for astronomy.
Jean D'Espagnet is known to have owned several books that had previously formed part of [[Michel de Montaigne|Montaigne's]] library, including his copy of [[De rerum natura]], in which his signature overwrites that of Montaigne's on the title-page.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titi Lucretii Cari De rerum natura libri sex (Montaigne.1.4.4)|url=http://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-MONTAIGNE-00001-00004-00004/9|publisher=Cambridge Digital Library|accessdate=9 July 2015|page=[i]/image 9}}</ref> In 1623 D'Espagnet wrote ''Arcanum Hermeticae philosophiae'' and ''Enchiridion physicae restitutae''.<ref>Written in Latin; D'Espagnet is occasionally called Spagnetus. The publication was anonymous. The attribution dates back to the middle of the seventeenth century.</ref>
